I think the most interesting use case for Huff is education. No guardrails, small bit of syntax sugar, mostly just mnenomic bytecode. Ultra-optimized contracts are rarely needed in prod (we're scaling eth!), but more smart contract developers knowing what is happening under the EVM's hood is a good thing for security.

On the flip side of "don't use Huff in prod", some of my favorite Huff projects that could actually be useful in the real world:
* https://github.com/Philogy/meth-weth
* https://github.com/jtriley-eth/ether-deck
* https://github.com/whitenois3/huff-snark-verifier (at least until Remco blows it out of the water soon)
Proptest is definitely one of the better crates. Has some great abstractions for building strategies for the different data types you're testing with and defining the properties themselves.
